<paragraph id="8BE9056D6277FFC671C72E69FE52FA74" blockId="45.[684,1213,1547,1736]" lastBlockId="46.[108,638,1418,1739]" lastPageId="46" pageId="45">
DIAGNOSIS: Both sexes of this species are easily recognized by T1–T4 with dense, appressed, apical yellow fasciae, legs orange, and wings yellow. The hypostomal tooth is strong in the male (fig. 5G), distinctive in frontal view as in 
<taxonomicName id="4C567EEE6277FFC577952EF2FD02F97F" authority="Gonzalez &amp; Griswold &amp; Engel, 2018" authorityName="Gonzalez &amp; Griswold &amp; Engel" authorityYear="2018" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kalina" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="B922D97F6277FFC577952EF2FD02F97F" italics="true" pageId="45">M. kalina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A21164046277FFC571F02ED3FCD8F97F" box="[763,820,1713,1736]" pageId="45" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
However, the latter species lacks the distinctive coloration of the wings and legs and the yellow fasciae on the terga.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
